WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.000
Coach Jessica: Hi Emily, thanks for meeting with me today.

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Emily: Hi Jessica. I'm excited to talk about differentiation and how I can better meet the needs of all my learners.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Coach Jessica: That's a fantastic goal, Emily.  It's so important to make sure every student has the opportunity to learn and grow in your classroom.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:35.000
Emily:  I agree. I've been trying to differentiate my lessons, but I'm always looking for ways to refine my approach and make it more effective. Sometimes it feels like I'm not reaching all of my students.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:50.000
Coach Jessica:  That's a common feeling, and it's great that you're reflecting on your practice and seeking ways to improve.  What does differentiation look like in your classroom right now?

00:00:51.000 --> 00:01:05.000
Emily:  Well, I try to provide different options for activities and assessments.  Sometimes I'll group students by ability or learning style, but it can be challenging to manage.  I often feel like I could be doing more.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:20.000
Coach Jessica:  I understand.  It can be tough to find the time and resources to differentiate effectively.  What are some of the biggest hurdles you face when it comes to differentiation?

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:35.000
Emily:  Honestly, planning is the biggest challenge.  It takes time to create different activities and materials for different learners.  And sometimes I feel overwhelmed and unsure where to even start.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:50.000
Coach Jessica:  Planning for differentiation can definitely feel daunting.  But there are strategies to streamline the process and make it more manageable.  We can explore those today.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:02:05.000
Emily:  That would be great.  I'm also sometimes unsure about which differentiation strategies are most effective for my students.  It's hard to know what will really make a difference.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:20.000
Coach Jessica:  We can definitely discuss that as well.  It's important to choose strategies that align with your students' needs, your teaching style, and the specific content you're teaching.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:35.000
Emily:  I'm teaching a lesson on quadratic equations next week, and I'm feeling a bit stuck on how to differentiate it effectively.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:50.000
Coach Jessica:  Okay, let's use that lesson as a case study.  Have you considered using tiered activities?

00:02:51.000 --> 00:03:00.000
Emily:  Tiered activities?  I've heard the term, but I'm not sure I fully understand how to use them.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:15.000
Coach Jessica:  Tiered activities are essentially different versions of the same activity, designed to meet the needs of learners at different levels of readiness.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:30.000
Emily:  So, I could have one activity for students who are already comfortable with quadratic equations, and another for those who are still struggling with the basics?

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:45.000
Coach Jessica:  Exactly.  And you could even have a third activity for students who are ready for a greater challenge and need to be pushed a bit further.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:04:00.000
Emily:  That's a good idea.  It would allow me to provide targeted support for each student's needs without leaving anyone behind.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:15.000
Coach Jessica:  Exactly.  And it can also help you manage the classroom more effectively, as students will be working on activities that are appropriately challenging for them.  This can help with engagement and behavior.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:30.000
Emily:  That's a big plus.  I'm always looking for ways to prevent boredom and frustration in my students.  When they're working at the right level, it makes a huge difference.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:45.000
Coach Jessica:  Absolutely.  Tiered activities can definitely help with that.  Now, let's brainstorm some specific tiered activities you could use for your quadratic equations lesson.  What are your initial thoughts?

00:04:46.000 --> 00:05:00.000
Emily:  Okay.  I'm thinking I could have one activity where students solve quadratic equations using the quadratic formula.  That's a core concept they need to master.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:15.000
Coach Jessica:  That's a good starting point.  And for students who are still struggling with the quadratic formula, you could provide them with a worksheet that guides them through the steps, maybe with some worked examples.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Emily:  That's helpful.  And for students who are ready for a challenge, I could have them solve quadratic equations by completing the square.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:45.000
Coach Jessica:  Excellent.  That's a more advanced method that will push their thinking and problem-solving skills.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:06:00.000
Emily:  I could also have them create their own word problems that involve quadratic equations and then have them trade problems with a partner to solve.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:15.000
Coach Jessica:  That's a great idea.  It encourages them to apply their knowledge in a real-world context and to think creatively.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:30.000
Emily:  I'm starting to see how tiered activities can make this lesson more engaging and accessible for all my students.  It feels less overwhelming now that we're breaking it down.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:45.000
Coach Jessica:  Exactly.  And it can also help you differentiate your instruction without feeling overwhelmed by planning.  It's about working smarter, not harder.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:07:00.000
Emily:  That's a big relief.  I sometimes feel like differentiation requires a ton of extra planning, and I already feel stretched for time.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:15.000
Coach Jessica:  It can, if you're not strategic about it.  But by focusing on high-impact strategies like tiered activities, you can differentiate effectively without spending hours and hours planning.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:30.000
Emily:  That's reassuring to hear.  I'm definitely going to try this approach for my quadratic equations lesson.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:45.000
Coach Jessica: Great. And I'd be happy to observe your lesson and provide feedback on the effectiveness of your differentiation.  It can be helpful to have another set of eyes in the classroom.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:08:00.000
Emily: That would be fantastic. I'm always eager to get feedback and improve my practice.  Especially when trying something new like this.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:15.000
Coach Jessica: Wonderful. Now, let's talk a bit about how you can assess the effectiveness of your differentiation, beyond just my observations. It's important to have multiple sources of information.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:30.000
Emily: Okay. I'm not always sure how to tell if my differentiation is actually making a difference for my students.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:45.000
Coach Jessica: One way to assess effectiveness is to simply observe your students during the lesson. Are they engaged? Are they challenged at the appropriate level? Are they able to demonstrate their understanding?

00:08:46.000 --> 00:09:00.000
Emily: That makes sense.  I can also collect student feedback on the activities.  I could have them do a quick reflection at the end.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:15.000
Coach Jessica: Exactly. You can ask them how they felt about the activity, whether it was too easy, too difficult, or just right. And you can also use formative assessments, like exit tickets or quick quizzes, to gauge their understanding of the concepts.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:30.000
Emily: That's helpful. I can also look at their work samples to see if they're applying the concepts correctly and making progress towards the learning goals.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:45.000
Coach Jessica: Absolutely. And you can compare their work on the different tiered activities to see if the differentiation is having the desired effect. Are students showing growth in the areas where they needed support?

00:09:46.000 --> 00:10:00.000
Emily: I'm starting to see how I can gather data to assess the effectiveness of my differentiation.  It's helpful to have these concrete strategies.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:15.000
Coach Jessica: It's all about being intentional and reflective in your practice. And remember, differentiation is not a one-size-fits-all approach.  What works for one class or one student might not work for another.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:30.000
Emily: That's true. I need to be flexible and adjust my strategies based on my students' needs and the specific learning objectives.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:45.000
Coach Jessica: Exactly. And don't be afraid to experiment and try new things.  Sometimes you have to try a few different approaches to find what works best.  The more you differentiate, the better you'll become at it.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:11:00.000
Emily: I'm excited to continue learning and growing in this area.  It's something I'm really passionate about.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:15.000
Coach Jessica: That's wonderful, Emily.  Now, shifting gears a bit, I know you mentioned that planning for differentiation can be a challenge.  What are some strategies you've tried in the past to make the planning process more manageable?

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:30.000
Emily:  Honestly, I haven't been very successful in streamlining the planning process.  I often end up spending hours creating different materials and activities, and it can be exhausting.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:45.000
Coach Jessica:  I understand.  It's important to find ways to work smarter, not harder.  One strategy is to start by focusing on your core lesson plan.  Make sure that your main lesson activities are engaging and effective for the majority of your students.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:12:00.000
Emily:  That makes sense.  I sometimes get so caught up in creating differentiated activities that I neglect the core lesson.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:15.000
Coach Jessica:  It's important to have a strong foundation.  Once you have your core lesson plan in place, you can then think about how to differentiate it for specific student needs.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:30.000
Emily:  Okay, that's helpful.  So, I should start by designing a lesson that works well for most of my students, and then adapt it from there.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:45.000
Coach Jessica:  Exactly.  And another strategy is to use existing resources whenever possible.  You don't have to create everything from scratch.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:13:00.000
Emily:  That's true.  There are a lot of great resources available online and in textbooks.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:15.000
Coach Jessica:  Exactly.  And you can also adapt existing materials to fit your students' needs.  For example, you could take a worksheet and modify it to create a tiered activity.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:30.000
Emily:  That's a good idea.  It would save me a lot of time.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:45.000
Coach Jessica:  And another strategy is to collaborate with other teachers.  You can share ideas and resources, and even co-plan lessons together.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:14:00.000
Emily:  That's a good point.  I have some great colleagues who are also passionate about differentiation.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:15.000
Coach Jessica:  Collaboration can be a powerful way to streamline the planning process and get new ideas.  And it can also help you stay motivated and supported.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:30.000
Emily:  I'll definitely try to collaborate more with my colleagues.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:45.000
Coach Jessica:  Great.  And finally, remember that differentiation doesn't have to be complicated.  Even small adjustments can make a big difference for your students.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:15:00.000
