Coach Jessica:  There are many apps and online tools that can help you with reflection.  Some even provide prompts and questions to guide your thinking.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:30.000
Emily:  That's helpful.  I sometimes struggle to know what to reflect on.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:45.000
Coach Jessica:  Those prompts can be a good starting point.  And you can also reflect on specific questions related to your differentiation practices.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:19:00.000
Emily:  Like, "What worked well in my differentiated lesson?" or "What could I have done differently?"

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:15.000
Coach Jessica:  Exactly.  And you can also reflect on the impact of your differentiation on student learning.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:30.000
Emily:  I can ask myself, "Did my differentiation help all students achieve the learning objectives?" or "Did it create a more inclusive and engaging learning environment?"

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:45.000
Coach Jessica:  Those are great questions, Emily.  And remember, reflection is not just about identifying areas for improvement.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:20:00.000
Emily:  That's true.  It's also about celebrating successes and acknowledging the progress I've made.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:15.000
Coach Jessica:  Exactly.  It's important to recognize your strengths and accomplishments as a teacher.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:30.000
Emily:  I'll try to be more mindful of that.  I tend to focus on what I need to improve and forget to acknowledge what I'm doing well.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:45.000
Coach Jessica:  It's a common tendency.  But it's important to celebrate your successes and give yourself credit for the hard work you're doing.

